deck_excerpt: A going-second list using Kaijus and Dark Ruler to board clear, and Krawlers to control future turns!
deck_description:
This list attempts to use Kaiju's removal with Krawler's control to play a very defensive going-second build. We want to slow down the game to a pace we can control and use our board-breakers and stun tools to keep the opponent from being able to meaningfully interract with our board. This is a part of a series I'm working on where I try to build as many variants of Krawler as I can. I'm doing so to stretch myself creatively, and to get to know the archetype better. I'll be going over what Krawlers do well/poorly, what the blending of these archetypes brings to the deck, as well as a card-by-card of the most notable additions to this list. This list was made possible by contributions from the Krawler discord, and user Marowak2000 in particular, so many thank!

 

Alright, Krawlers: what do they do well, what do they struggle with, and what does their partner in this build (Kaiju) bring to the table? Krawlers have a very strong grind game. Each Krawler you get to stick on field is a renewable effect to either pop a card, summon a Krawler from GY or hand, or to return 2 cards from GY to hand (just the Krawlers in this list). They can flood the board, thanks to Soma, and have a strong Skill Drain monster in Deus X-Krawler, not to mention all of the Krawlers (except Soma) float into more Krawlers! The downside is that these are still flip-monsters, and as such they needs lots of support to get the best out of them. A going-first build has to contend with the opponent's hand traps and interruption as well as board clears like Lightning Storm, Raigeki, and Harpie's Feather Duster. Kaijus help the Krawlers generally slow, setup-oriented gameplan by allowing us to go second. We let the opponent make their best board, and then we Dark Ruler, Interrupted Kaiju Slumber, and just plain old Kaiju the opponent's best sources of interruption before making our board. By going second, we avoid the most damaging removal for Krawlers (when they're face-down and can't float), and get many of the opponent's most powerful mosnters out of the way. One of the main risks of this approach is if the opponent is playing a Trap/Quickplay deck like Labrynth or Runic, in which case we will need to side into other board-breaking options.

 

Our Kaiju package is 2 Gadarla, 2 Gameciel, 3 Interrupted Kaiju Slumber, 1 Kyoutou Waterfront (for the grind game), and 1 Thunder King (searchable off of Deus X-Krawler's floating effect).We're on Beetrooper Scale Bomber and Magical Hound as our Small World bridges, but they both do work for the deck; Scale Bomber is an extender and Magical Hound can bounce a floodgate. We are on 1 World Armor for a Girsu line ending on Equimax, using our 1 World Legacy Succession. We are on 1 Knightmare Corruptor Iblee to further control our opponent's board, but she may not be necessary. We are on 2 World Legacy Mind Meld, usually to send off of Girsu to guarantee Deus X-Krawler, and we play 2 copies to lower the chance of drawing both. The three flip Spell/Traps in this list are played at 2 each: Sol and Luna(EDIT: now at 3), Junk Sleep, and World Legacy Pawns. I'm considering lpaying Sol and Luna at 3; it is a hard once-per-turn, but it is invaluable in breaking boards and activating Krawler flip-effects (I've since updated the list with Sol and Luna at 3). Junk Sleep has niche uses when we want to activate more than one Krawler at once, and it flips all of our monsters face-down at the end of each turn, which is a great way to re-use Soma's effect. World Legacy Pawns only targets one monster, but it is searchable off of Lib and Survivor, and it can be activated more freely than Junk Sleep's reactive activation. In the extra deck we have the usual suspects like I:P Masquerena, Avramax and the Knightmares. Since we are going second, Dharc can often steal a card out of the opponent's GY. We can make Wina off of two flip-monsters and Girsu, using Shaddoll Construct to perform the fusion. Gigantic Spright lets us set up the Iblee line and link off into Dharc, I:P Masquerena, or another Link 2.

 

Our main line of play is, as said above, going second. If we open Dark Ruler, IKS, or Kaiju(s) we can pressure the opponent's field and remove their most critical monsters. Once we have done so, we need to mop up the rest of their board. We have a few options for this, most of which start with Girsu. Normal Girsu, pitch Mind Meld, make the Girsu token, use Soma to flip Girsu face-down and summon Soma. Activate Soma to summon 2 more face-up Krawlers from deck, link Soma and the token for Lib, activate Lib to set Pawns, link the small Krawlers for Shaddoll Construct and make Winda with the Construct and the face-down Girsu. This line is only beneficial if you cleared most of the opponent's board before going for it. If the opponent still has a lot of threats still in play, start instead by normal summoning Girsu and sending World Armor to the GY. Make Lib (Soma/Girsu token) and search Succession. Activate Succession summoning back World Armor, and searching Survivor/Pawns/Mind Meld (depending on what you need). Link off for either Avramax or Equimax and attack the rest of the opponent's board. If we start with Soma and another normal-summonable monster instead, we summon the monster, activate and summon Soma, and use Soma to summon 2 more Krawlers from deck. Link off for I:P Masquerena, then Equimax, attacking into the Kaiju you positioned so that Equimax would be pointing to it. Other plays we can make to clear boards include setting Spine and using Sol and Luna to flip Spine up and an opponent's monster face-down, then using Spine to pop an opponent's monster. To use Iblee, we need Soma and any normal-summonable monster in hand. Normal summon, then special Soma by flipping that monster face-down, use Soma to summon 2 Krawlers, either 1 face-up or both face-up. Overlay for Gigantic, use Gigantic to summon Iblee, then link Iblee and another monster off for any Link 2 monster, summoning Iblee to the opponent's field.

 

The Small World bridgs are as follows:

Starter  ->  Bridge  ->  Goal

Gameciel / Any Krawler / Scale Bomber  ->  Gadarla  ->  Gameciel / Any Krawler / Scale Bomber

Gadarla / Any Krawler  ->  Scale Bomber  ->  Any Krawler / Gadarla

World Armor / Any Krawler / Girsu  ->  Magical Hound  ->  World Armor / Any Krawler / Girsu

Soma / Magical Hound  ->  World Armor  ->  Soma / Magical Hound

Thunder King / Iblee / Magical Hound / Scale Bomber  ->  Krawler Spine  ->  Thunder King / Iblee / Magical Hound / Scale Bomber

Deus X-Krawler / Spine   ->  Thunder King  ->  Deus X-Krawler / Spine

 

The Side Deck is just a collection of possible includes and ideas for alternative takes on this build.

Thanks so much for reading my decklist and explaination! Please leave a comment to let me know what you think; what would you change in the build, or what questions do you have regarding the deck! I hope you have a great day!

A wacky deck that aims to quickly banish cards from your opponent's hand and deck until they're completely out for a Deck Out victory!

Full of lots of different tools to stall and reset the field while very rapidly churning through your opponent's cards and removing them from play, all the while using Soul Absorbtion for huge healing for every card banished. 

For a big game-ender, tribute their more dangerous monsters into Lava Golem, then bait out his 3000 damage hit (or attack it with one of your 0 ATK monsters) to trigger Inferno Tempest and banish every monster from their deck and GY (if Soul Absorption's on the field this will also heal you for tens of thousands)!

If milling's not working and you need damage, tribute some of your many continuous spells and traps into Metaltron, if you do it right he'll be uneffected by any card effects, and when destroyed, can summon several powerful options from the extra deck (Steam Train King's my personal favorite).

---

Good Against: Decks that rely on getting things in and out of the graveyard, have long chains of special summons (because Soul Levy punishes that hard), or that already thin themselves (with Pot of Desires, Card Destruction, Magical Mallet, ect.)

Real Bad Against: Decks that want their cards banished, decks with egregious amounts of of destruction (especially backline), 60 card decks, and pretty much anything meta

deck_excerpt: Ghostrick control with Nekomusume! Uses the Krawler engine to make Gigantic Spright or UDF.
deck_description:
This is another deck in a series of lists I've been creating where I see how many Krawler build I can put together. I'm going for creativity, originality, and hopefully viability. This list blends Krawlers with Ghostricks, an archetype either known for its wild Extra Deck combo enablers or its slow Main Deck control options. I'm blending a little of both in a build that balances control and combo, board-breaking and board-protecting.  If you enjoy this list, please check out some of the other Krawler builds that I've created! I'll be breaking down the deck concept, the card choices, and a few combo lines down below.

 

Krawlers, as an archetype, lend themselves to control strategies, as do most flip-effect decks. The easiest way of flipping up a card is simply waiting for your opponent to attack into it, or to wait until your next turn to flip it up. With the introduction of Krawler Soma, Krawlers also have combo plays. They can get 3 monsters face-up on the board very easily, but don't have the strongest Extra Deck tools to take advantage of this. Ghostricks are similar to Krawlers, though they are not technically flip monsters. Their Main Deck cards are mostly focused around controlling the opponent's plays while accruing card advantage, but their Extra Deck is all about the combo! Any level 1, 2, or 3 Ghostrick Xyz mon can make Angel of Mischief, who can detatch to search a Ghostrick Spell/Trap, and the level 1 and 3 Xyz mons return cards from GY to hand when they are sent there. This makes UDF very accessible, and if you have a Ghostrick field spell, Zeus is also on the table (as you can attack directly). So, Krawlers flood the board with monsters that we can Xyz climb with, and the Ghostrick ED lets us take advantage of the monsters on field. There is a small problem; Soma needs a face-up monster to summon itself, and all of the main deck Ghostricks cannot be summoned face-up unless their is already another face-up Ghostrick monster. We solve this problem with Parallel Exceed and Tour Guide, but there are more capable builds. I will also be building a Spright build that really ramps up this deck's speed and ability to play through interruption, but for now I'm focusing on pure Ghostrick Krawler.

 

Our main combo starter is Parallel Exceed, run at 3. If we open this card and any Ghostrick, we can make Angel of Mischief and search a card. If we also open Soma (run at 3), its full combo to UDF and Necrovalley. If, instead, we open Parallel Exceed and Tour Guide (run at 2), that also gets us UDF, and often Necrovalley (depending on the other cards in hand). We run just one copy of Krawler Glial, one of Axon,and one Spine, the summons off of Soma. This is a very tight list, and though I would love to run more Krawlers, I simply don't have the room (which is why Tour Guide is at 2). For the Ghostricks, we run 1 Jiangshi (searches Mary/Lantern), 1 Fairy (returns Ghostrick cards from GY to field), 1 Nekomusume (one of our main floodgates), 1 Doll (flips the whole board face-down in the end phase), and 1 Lantern with 1 Mary (our combat tricks). This list could be trimmed by removing Jiangshi, Lantern, and Mary, but I prefer to leave them in for now. To protect our board, we're on 3 Lord of the Heavenly Prison and 3 Calamity Upon the Hidden City, which also buffs our mons. We run 2 Shot and 2 Scare, they are easily searchable, but we want multiples for future turns. Ghostrick Renovation gets us to Necrovalley, and Ghostrick Night keeps the opponent's mons face-down. Kurikara Divincarnate is our primary board breaker, used either going second or on our second turn, it lets us respond to the opponent's monster effects by tributing them for cost and summoning a big beater. Finally, our Small World bridges (there are a lot). Lady of the Labrynth can get us into Parallel Exceed, and she is also a great draw, letting us search one-ofs like Lost Wind or Compulsory Evacuation Device. Mothman is a bridge to and from the Krawlers, and can work as a risky card draw option. Since Parallel Exceed is so important in this list, we have another way of bridging into them with Micro Coder.

 

In the extra deck, we're on all of the Ghostricks, the UDF line, Gigantic Spright (who can summon Nekomusume), Dharc to steal an opponent's mon, Almiraj (if we have Parallel and a Small Krawler in hand), and Knightmare Unicorn. We are running Sky Calvalry Centaurea to make Zeus off of the Soma summons, usually when we have to go second.

 

This deck has quite a few interesting lines!

Our basic combos are as follows:

Parallel and a Ghostrick: Set the Ghostrick, and link into Festival. Activate Parallel, summoning Parallel from hand, then Parallel from deck. Make Angel with the two, then detatch to search. If we have the field spell or Renovations in hand, search the one you don't have and activate the field spell with a set Renovations, we can then go into Necrovalley on the opponent's turn. If you don't have either of those, grap Shot to summon back the Ghostrick in GY and flip them down, or Scare if you have a Shot already in hand.

Parallel and a Krawler/MicroCoder: Summon the Krawler, then link them off for Almiraj. Follow the steps in the combo above, starting when you first summon Parallel Exceed.

Tour Guide: Summon Tour Guide, special summoning Tour Guide from deck. Overlay for Alucard, overlay him for Angel. Detatch one of the Guides to search Shot, then link Angel off for Festival. Trigger Alucard in Gy (not a once-per-turn) to add Angel back to the ED, then Shot back the Alucard. Overlay again for Angel, then detatch the Alucard to search Scare/Mansion/Renovations (use the combo above to determine what to search). When Alucard hits the GY, add back Shot for next turn (sadly, this is a once-per-turn).

Soma and Scale Bomber / Mothman / Krawler / Micro Coder: Normal the starter (level <=4 mon) and flip them down to summon Soma. Use Soma, summoning two Krawlers from deck, one face-up the other face-down. Overlay your two face-up monsters into Socuteboss, overlaying her for Angel. Detatch Socuteboss to search Shot, Shot back Socuteboss and make another Angel. Detatch Socuteboss again to search Scare, then overlay the two Angels for Utopic Future. Overlay for Utopic Draco Future, set your Scare and you're all set!

 

More involved combos:

Parallel, a Ghostrick, and Soma: Follow the same steps for the combo above with Parallel and a Ghostrick, searching Renovations or Mansion. Your board should now be Ghostrick Festival and Ghostrick Angel of Mischief. Summon Soma by flipping down the Angel, activate Soma to summon 2 Krawlers, one face-up the other face-down. Make UDF using the steps above, but search Renovations or Mansion instead of Scare (unless you have both in hand). Activate the field spell and set Renovations, and you have a board with Necrovalley on the opponent's turn, UDF, and Festival.

Parallel, a Ghostrick, and Soma: For this combo, our goal is not UDF, but rather Nekomusume. Follow the Parallel and Ghostrick combo, ending on Festival and Angel, but search Ghostrick Scare instead of Renovations or Mansion. Summon the Soma by flipping down Angel, then summon one Krawler face-up, the other face-down. Overlay the two face-up monsters into Gigantic Spright, then detatch to summon Nekomusume from deck. You then have Festival, Gigantic, Nekomusume, a face-down Krawler and a face-down Angel, and Scare set.

Parallel and Tour Guide: Perform the Tour Guide combo from the Tour Guide section above, but only to the point where you have searched Shot and linked off Angel for Festival. Activate the Parallel in hand and the Alucard in GY, summoning the Parallel and adding back the Angel with Alucard. Summon the second Parallel using the firsts effect. Overlay for Angel, searching Mansion afterwards. Shot back Alucard and overlay for Angel. Detatch Alucard from Angel to search Renovations, adding back the Shot from GY when Alucard is sent there. Overlay the 2 Angels for Utopic Future, then into Utopic Draco Future. You will end with Festival, UDF, and Necrovalley live.

Tour Guide and Soma: Perfom the Tour Guide combo from the Tour Guide Section above, ending on just the first Angel on field after having searched Shot. Flip down Angel to summon Soma, use Soma to Summon 2 Krawlers, one face-down, the other face-up. From here you can either fallow the first Parallel/Ghostrick/Soma combo to end on UDF or the second to end on Nekomusume.

 

 

Alright, I'm basically done, now just to describe the many Small World bridges!

Starter  ->  Bridge  ->  Goal

Any Dark Monster (except Lantern) / Divincarnate / Spine / Parallel Exceed  ->  Micro Codeer  ->  Any Dark but Lantern / Divincarnate / Spine / Parallel

Any Krawler / Any Dark  ->  Mothman  ->  Any Krawler / Any Dark

Any Dark (not LotHP / Mary / Lantern) / Parallel  ->  Lady of the Labrynth  ->  Any Dark (not LotHP / Mary / Lantern) / Parallel

 Soma / Micro Coder / Lady  ->  Parallel Exceed ->  Soma / Micro Coder / Lady

Parallel / Mothman  ->  Soma  ->  Parallel / Mothman

Any Dark (not Lady)  ->  LotHP  ->  Any Dark (not Lady)

 

 

Whew! Thank you for reading all of that (some? none? Idk)! Hopefully you found this informative, or at the very least entertaining. I appreciate your time, and woudl love to hear what you think about the list! Can it be improved? What would your build look like? Let me know down below!

deck_excerpt: Recently I'm experimenting on Dueling Nexus with the P.U.N.K. engine, without getting too much out of my comfort zone.
deck_description:
As a PK Fire player, I'm struggling to fit in this new meta and I'm feeling like is time to change a bit this routine. Welcome P.U.N.K.s and as a metalhead I'm more than happy about it. Jokes aside, P.U.N.K. is a fun and fast engine that works marvelously with PKs. You still have your The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche and Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess combo, plus a bunch of really powefull Synchros in your endboard, namely a negate in Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss .

This time the sidedeck is more thought out, I feel that more than two Nibiru, the Primal Being are useless, adding one Dinowrestler Pankratops makes your side a bit more varied. It adds some "equalizer" card such Triple Tactics Talent and Evenly Matched , near the a main-decked Dark Ruler No More , I would side them removing the PSY-Frame package. No hand traps beside PSY-Framegear Gamma to have a little more space for the combo pieces, also because they're necessary to stop Tearalaments and Sprights in my humble opinion, feel free to change my mind.

deck_excerpt: All Gas All Red-Eyes Slash Dragon
deck_description: All Gas All Red-Eyes Slash Dragon. Ignore Forbidden Lists. Crush your friends on the playground!
So this build is made to specifically be hateful against tearalaments. Not much else. Although dark law and crow/belle hurt other decks pretty good too.
A mixture of Skull servant and other zombie cards. Basic as all hell, not really a pro deck, but maybe you can have fun with it.

This is a deck for Yu-Gi-Oh! 5DS's World Championship 2011: Over the Nexus. You can summon Exodia turn 1, but if you can't do that, you might still be able to fight back like a normal deck.

The main draw engines are Tuningware De-synchro (Ideally 3 draws per de-synchro, 2 if you use it on Formula Synchron, or, in the worst case, 1. And when you run out of De-Synchro, instead of making a 3 draw synchro summon if possible, i recommend to get up to 6 draws by summoning Formula Synchron instead), Royal Magical Library and Bamboo Sword. Cup of Ace is there too if you're lucky enough.

In this game Brionac is Pre-errata, and for some reason Dark End Dragon doesn't target.

If you prefer it to be 40 card and oriented towards a first turn win, move Malicious to the side, this way it's more consistent on setting up the draw engines but considerably weaker when you either brick or can't recover all pieces of Exodia.

When it comes to dueling, you can summon 2 Shooting Star Dragon with a 5 card combo (if you draw Monster reborn with the draws you get along the way + after), or De-Synchro Mistwurm to clear a field, equip Armory Arm to a Synchro, use De-Synchro on your opponent, etc.

Malicious doubles as discard fooder/Foolish target and a LV7/8 Synchro material (with it you can summon two Shooting Star Dragon with a 5 card combo). It's also good as not to run out of Foolish Burial targets.

Remember not to de-synchro your monsters if the materials are no longer in the GY (careful with Plaguespreader Zombie)

If you brick and discard the head of Exodia, make sure to save Monster reborn to summon it and bring it back to hand with Zephyros (who can also be used for synchro summoning, to get more discard fooder and for an extra spell activation. Remember that in Tag Duels both you and your partner can use it's effect. If you prefer Monster Reincarnation replace it).

If you can't recover all pieces of Exodia, focus on dueling.

If you have to end your turn and had activated Into the Void, set your spells beforehand. If you have Plaguespreader in GY, you might also be able to save a card from being discarded.

I know Pot of Avarice is a weird pick for a Exodia deck, but it can give a second chance to use Machine Duplication and/or Royal Library, and that is a chance to end the duel in the same turn.

If you don't like Cup of Ace, i left an alternative on the side deck. And if you want more discard fooder, Thunder Dragon is there too.
Deck for tcg competition

deck_name: Burn Deck ( I swear it's not volcanics)
deck_description: ........but maybe it's not volcanics.....
Look, I know you're watching House of the Dragon. I said I wouldn't watch it too but I know I'm a liar. What's your excuse?

To mill and have access to an easy monster engine. A fun deck but can be high risk..

 

Essentially every starting hand will give you access to the runick mill engine. 50 cards in main deck (40 are the base runick engine + 4 branded engine + a few additions like prankratops, nibiru, iris that are useful even if not conducting battle phase). You can add more spell/trap/negate options taking this to a 55-60 card deck from the listed side deck. 

 

- Essentially, by getting fountain out there is a good chance you will mill out your opponent quickly, or atleast remove many meaningful cards and potential sequences so long as you have runick quickplay spells to activate.

- Mystic mine fits in nicely with this decks style as well. Can be used to slow down your opponent as you mill them out.

- Our trickstar trap should be renamed runick reincarnation.

- The runick fusions are usually the main extra deck cards accessed to add either a negate or to pop a card when needed, however, if your mill is destructive to the cards they have access to, the branded cards add an engine to help to hit them with a different tactic, especially towards the end. You will most likely have to skip a battle phase however; OR it can help to prevent being fully exposed at times. It is not overly powerful, but is an alternative to a pure spell + negates runick deck.

deck_excerpt: Krawlers and Penguins! Penguins and Krawlers! What more do you need!
deck_description:
Hello again! This is part of a series of decks where I try to make as many Krawler-creations as I can, blending archetypes to find interesting and unusual builds! This build seeks to combine the Krawler's ability to flood the board and flip down monsters with Penguin's ability to summon Squire when we flip-down our monsters, opening up the possibility for Synchro plays. If you enjoy this list or my description, please check out some of the other decks I've build within this series! I'll be going through the archetypes, a deck breakdown, and combo lines down below.

 

In this deck, Krawlers are good for a few reasons: we can make Utopic Draco Future relatively easily, we can use Girso to set Deus X-Krawler and Pawns to our field, and we can make Winda off of a hand with Soma and Girsu. We are running a very trim Krawler package to accomplish this, and maxxing out on Small World to find our missing combo pieces. The Penguins allow us to go into Synchro plays off of Penguin Squire. Squire can special summon itself whenever we flip a card face-down, or summon it in face-down defense position, which we can do quite easily. This is really powerful, however Squire locks us into Water Synchro summons. At first this may seem like a hard wall, but remember, Halq is still legal! Squire and any other card becomes Halq and a search for another tuner (in this casel, Ghost Belle)! What this list is meant to do is show you the possibilities of this combination, and to do so we are running essentially no interruption or board breaking tools. This is probably not advisable for a more competitive build, but if we go first we can usually pop-off, given that the whole deck is just gas.

 

So, what are we playing? The Krawler portion of this list is just Deus X, 3 Soma, Spine and 2 Glial. Girsu is sort of an honorary Krawler, so we'll count them as well! We're on Mind Meld and Pawns for our Girsu / Lib combo. The Penguins make up the meat of this list. The Great Emperor Penguin is quite powerful, but also powerfully bricky so he stays at 1. Squire, on the other hand, is a card we always want to see, so they're at 3. One each of Nopenguin, Penguin Ninja, Puny Penguin, and Penguin Cleric round out our Penguin support core, and the 2 Penguin Soldier stand in as the Penguin we're going to be searching and setting a lot of. We run 3 Small World to search Soma, Girsu, or Squire, and Iblee, Mitsu, and Cartorhyn are our bridges. The Ghostrick / UDF package requires that we run Shot, and Scare is a nice card to grab off of the combo as well. Finally, we are running 3 Sol and Luna (a great flip card) and 3 Solemn Judgement (to stop our board from being broken). In the Extra Deck, we're on a small Shaddoll package to make Winda, the UDF package, I:P and Avramax, Lib, and Halq. The Synchros I wanted to run are Naturia Beast, Penguin Squire, Shooting Riser, and Chengying (mostly to synergize with the Nopenguin banishes).

 

What can this deck do? I'll go over some basic combos, and then work in our stronger combos that require more specific combinations of cards in hand.

Starting hand:

Soma and any normal-summonable monster: Normal the monster and activate Soma in hand, flipping down the monster and special-summoning Soma. Activate Soma to summon 1 Krawler face-up and 1 face-down. Overlay the face-up Krawler and Soma into Socuteboss, and overlay her into Angel of Mischief. Detatch Socuteboss to search Ghostrick Shot, then Shot back Socuteboss. Overlay her again for another Angel of Mischief, detatching again for Scare this time. Overlay the two Angels for Utopic Future, then again for Utopic Draco Future. End board is UDF, a set Krawler, and a set Scare.

Girsu: Normal Girsu, sending Mind Meld to GY. Activate Girsu to make a token on each field, then link off Girsu and the token for Lib. Activate Lib to set Pawns to the field, then activate the Mind Meld in GY to summon Deus X to the field.

Royal Penguins Garden: Activate the Garden, searching Emperor Penguin. Activate Garden again to reduce the level of Emperor and discard a card. Summon Emperor, then tribute them to summon Squire and Puny Penguin. Synch off these monsters for Penguin Brave, then use its effect to set Penguin Soldier to the field. If you drew the Puny Penguin, we can adjust so long as we draw / search Squire. Instead of summoning Puny and Squire off of Emperor, summon Ninja and Soldier. Use Ninja to flip-down Soldier which will allow you to special summon Squire, then you can lower Squire's level by 1. Activate Squire to flip-up Soldier (not activating its effect, unless the opponent has mons on board) and make Penguin Brave, setting another Soldier from deck to field.

 

Here are some more involved combo lines:

Soma and Girsu: Normal Girsu, sending Mind Meld, and make a token. Activate Soma to summon itself and flip-down Girsu. Use Soma to summon 2 face-up Krawlers, then link Soma and the token for Lib, setting Pawns with her effect. Link the two flip-Krawlers off for Construct, then use Construct's effect to fuse with Girsu to make Winda. Finally, activate Mind Meld in the GY to summon Deus X to a zone Lib points to.

Girsu and Penguin Squire: Perform the Girsu combo, but summon a level 2 Krawler off of Mind Meld, not Deus X. Your board should be Lib, Pawns set, and a set Krawler. When that Krawler is summoned, trigger Squire to summon itself, and reduce its level by 1. Activate Squire to flip-up the Krawler, then you can make Penguin Brave, setting Soldier from deck. You could also link the Squire and the Krawler away for I:P Masquerena and make Avramax. Alternatively, a potentially more powerful play would be to link Girsu and the token off for Atrifact Dagda, summoning the Krawler off of Mind Meld, activating Squire to summon itself. When Squire uses its on-field effect to reduce its level, use Dagda to set a Scythe from deck. This list doesn't contain these cards, to show more variety in potential combos, but you could make your own list using these lines.

Soma and Squire and a normal-summonable mon: Summon the monster and flip it down with Soma to summon Soma. On that flip-down, trigger Squire to summon Squire. Activate Soma to summon 1 face-up Krawler and 1 face-down Krawler, then link Soma and Squire off for Halq, summoning Ghost Belle from deck. Synch off the Ghost Belle and the face-up Krawler for Naturia Beast. This play gets much more powerful if you have Mitsu or Cartorhyn in hand. If you do, make sure to summon both Krawlers off of Soma face-up, then either summon Mitsu at the end of the combo, or Cartorhyn when you have face-up Water and Earth mons (remember, Halq is Water). Then, overlay these 2 face up mons (a Krawler and Mitsu/Cartorhyn) for Socuteboss, then follow the above combo to make UDF. End board, optimally, is Naturia Beast, Halq, and UDF. On the opponent's turn, Halq can tag out for Shooting Riser, who will send a level 2 mon to make their level 5. When the opponent has run out of Spells, or they are trying to move into the Battle Phase, synch Riser and Beast for Chengying.

Soma and Penguins Garden: You can either perform the Squire / Soma combo above, or a combo with Soma and Emperor. Activate the Garden, grabbing Nopenguin. Activate Garden's level lowering effect to reduce Emperor's level by discarding Nopenguin. Summon and tribute Emperor, which will trigger Nopenguin to summon itself. off of Emperor, summon Squire and Soldier. Flip Soldier down to summon Soma, then link off Squire and Nopenguin for Halq, summoning Ghost Belle. Activate Soma to summon 2 Krawlers. Your board should be similar to the one built in the combo above (Soma and Squire). This is your branch point, where depening on your cards in hand, you can either make Nat Beast, Halq, and two set mons, or Nat Beast, Halq, a set Soldier, and UDF.

One of the craziest hands this deck can produce is Soma, Girsu, Squire, and Garden: Activate Garden to grab Nopenguin, use Garden to decrease Squire's level by pitching Nopenguin. Summon Girsu, pitching Mind Meld and create a token, then flip Girsu down to summon Soma. Use Soma to summon 2 face-up Krawlers, then Make Lib with Soma and the token. Make Shaddoll Construct with the two face-up Krawlers, leaving an open space near where the link-arrow is pointed. Here you do one of two things, so remember this break-point. Lets play a bit safe, and summon Deus X off of Mind Meld to the open space near Construct. This lets us summon Squire from hand, which will trigger Nopenguin to summon itself from Gy. Reduce Squire's level by 1 so it will now be at 3 (the previous Garden activation lowered it by 1 as well), and you can synch off the penguins for Penguin Brave, summoning Soldier, then fusion summon Winda using Construct and the face-down Girsu. This creates a board with a face-down Soldier and Deus X, Penguin Brave, Winda, and Lib. Alternatively, at the break point, use Mind Meld to summon a level 2 Krawler from deck, then summon Squire and Nopenguin off of their triggers. Activate Squire to flip-up the face-down Krawler. Then, if you have an extender like Mitsu or Cartorhyn, get ready to summon them. Link Squire and Lib for Halq, summoning Ghost Belle who will Synch with the Krawler for Nat Beast. Summon your extender, then link them off with Nopenguiin for I:P Masquerena. Use I:P and Halq to make Avramax, then make Winda with Construct and the face-down Girsu. This end board is Avramax with I:P's protection, Naturia Beast, and Winda.

 

Whew! Enough of all that, here's the Small World Bridges:

Starter  ->  Bridge  ->  Goal

Any Krawler / Any non-level 2 Water mon / Iblee  ->  Insect Ninja Mitsu  ->  Any Krawler / Any non-level 2 Water / Iblee

Level 2 Krawler / Non-level 2 Water mon / Iblee  ->  Cartorhyn the Hidden Gem  ->  Level 2 Krawler / Non-level 2 Water Mon / Iblee

Any Level 2 Mon / Girsu / Ghost Belle ->  Iblee  ->  Any Level 2 Mon / Girsu / Ghost Belle

Any Krawler / Iblee ->  Ghost Belle  ->  Any Krawler / Iblee

 

 This one was a long one! I hope its been a fun and interesting read, and if not that at least a goofy list that you can enjoy! I'd love to see your version of a Krawler Penguin list, or even combos that are more optimal that the ones I've given! Maybe you can come up with a list that makes stronger end-boards, or one that has more interruption and going-second tools? Whatever the case, I'd love to hear your thoughts in the comments! Thanks, and take care!

deck_excerpt: P.U.N.K. Spright Tearlaments / YCS Rio de Janeiro Top 32
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Patrick Hoban

Tournament: YCS Rio de Janeiro - August 27th 2022

Placement: Top 32

Weather Painter has gained 2 very good pieces of legacy Support from DIFO in The Weather Painter Moonbow and The Weather Forcast. Not only do these cards make the Deck more consistent, but it also allows you to have easier access to the strongest part of your Deck that used to be inaccessible for years, The Weather Painter Rainbow. 

Our Weather Painter monsters consist of 1 The Weather Painter Aurora, 3 The Weather Painter Thunder, 3 The Weather Painter Cloud, 3 The Weather Painter Snow, and 1 The Weather Painter Rain. The Weather Painters have a playstyle where they are given additional effects from their Continuous Spell/Trap lineup based on what column they are in. They banish themselves for cost in order to activate these effects and return during the next Standby Phase. Aurora protects all of your Weather Painter Spells/Traps from being targeted or destroyed. You will almost never use her Normal Summon effect because you want to keep all of your Weather Painter monsters in rotation and using 1 for a Tribute Summon is not worth it. Thunder has the effect to send a Continuous Spell/Trap you control to the GY to place 1 The Weather Spell/Trap from your Deck in your Spell/Trap Zone. Notably, you cannot get The Weather Forcast with this effect since it has to place them in the Spell/Trap Zone which means that Field Spells are unapplicable. Also keep in mind that it also sends the card for cost, so you can use this to send a Floodgate you control to the GY to access your plays once you've hindered your opponent's plays enough. Cloud can target up to 2 The Weather Spells/Traps from your GY and place them face-up in your Spell/Trap Zone when another The Weather card you control is sent to the GY. It synergizes with The Weather Forcast's effect to use your The Weather Spells/Traps as Link Material as Cloud just gets them right back. Snow places a The Weather Spell/Trap from your Deck face-up in your Spell/Trap Zone on Normal Summon which is really good for the Deck. Rain places a The Weather Spell/Trap from your hand face-up if it is Special Summoned. It is not very good, but it is another Weather Painter name at the very least and it is seemingly more playable than The Weather Painter Sun. We also play 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being since there are many situations where your Weather Painters will not be on the field, so you don't suffer from Nibiru Tributing your own monsters.

For our Weather Spells/Traps, we play 3 The Weather Snowy Canvas, 1 The Weather Rainy Canvas, 3 The Weather Forcast, 2 The Weather Rainbowy Canvas, and 1 The Weather Thundery Canvas. The Weather Painter Continuous Spell/Traps give all Weather Painter monsters in your Main Monster Zones in the same column and the adjacent columns a unique effect. Snowy Canvas allows your Weather Painter to banish itself to search any The Weather Card from Deck. Rainy Canvas allows your Weather Painter to banish itself to return a Spell/Trap your opponent controls and you can keep on doing this if you have other Weather Painters who've gained the effect. Rainbowy Canvas banishes the Weather Painter to Special a Weather Painter from Deck if your opponent controls a monster. Thundery Canvas banishes the Weather Painter to return the monster its battling to the hand at the start of the Damage Step. The Weather Forcast is a Field Spell that places a Weather Spell/Trap from Deck face-up upon activation, it gives you an Extra Normal Summon of a Weather Painter, and it allows you to use your The Weather Spell/Traps as Link Material. This gives much more consistency as well as an easier way to access The Weather Painter Rainbow.  We also play 3 Pot of Prosperity to dig for cards, 1 Terraforming to search The Weather Forcast, 3 Infinite Impermanence, 3 Skill Drain, 3 Anti-Spell Fragrance, and 3 Solemn Strike. Skill Drain is good as your Weather Painters banish themselves as cost, so they will not be hindered by Skill Drain. Your effects "place" The Weather Spell/Traps face-up instead of activating them, so Anti-Spell doesn't hinder you either. 

We will rarely go into the Extra Deck outside of our Weather Painter Link Monsters. Elder Entity N'tss and Garura, Wings of Resonant Life are Ultimate Slayer Targets as N'tss can destroy a card and Garura can Draw a card. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, 1 Downerd Magician, 1 The Phantom Knights of Break Sword, and 1 Number 49: Fortune Tune as an Xyz package. 1 World Ocean Dragon - Zealantis and 1 Accesscode Talker. Accesscode will not have that many pops since you are Link Summoning very little in this Deck, but it can be used as Material for Zealantis for for board-clearing. 1 Knightmare Unicorn, 1 Wynn the Wind Charmer, Verdant, and 1 Lyna the Light Charmer, Lustrous. You can play any combination of Charmer Links including Aussa the Earth Charmer, Immovable, Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy, and Eria the Water Charmer, Gentle. 2 The Weather Painter Rainbow and 2 The Weather Painter Moonbow. Rainbow can send itself to the GY to negate a Special Summon and it makes all of the Weather Painter monsters it points to into omni-negates. Moonbow floats into Rainbow on destruction and it allows the Weather Painters it points to the effect to banish a monster your opponent controls until the next Standby Phase. You mainly want to Summon Rainbow as it has more application, but Moonbow can come up and it even floats into Rainbow eitherway. 

Side Deck, we are playing 3 Kaijus, any of your choice, 1 Dinowrestler Pankratops for removal, 3 Raigeki, 3 Ultimate Slayer, 1 Dimensional Fissure, 3 Torrential Tribute, and 1 Macro Cosmos. Cards like Dimension Fissure, Macro Cosmos, and Dimension Shifter are completely playable in Weather Painter, but it does interfere with The Weather Painter Cloud's effect, so it is best to only play them when it hurts the opponent more than you.

Creator: Chromite

deck_excerpt: It may be a rogue deck in this format but it can still perform and challenge the Meta!
deck_description: It is a relatively mid-priced deck, but of course you can make it even cheaper by removing Savage, Apollousa and Borrelsword (you can use Borreload Dragon, Scrap Dragon, Omega or multiple copies of Evolzar Monsters) and even replace Harpie's with Twin Twisters or Imperm with other traps that negate monster effects and are perfect fit for your budget.You can do any changes that you like in the deck obviously (as long as they work), but I consider this one to be a very consistent Dinosmasher Variant. Nemeses Keystone is necessary to recycle Misc and works perfectly with Gallant Granite (let's hope Misc will at least get back to 2 copies). Scrap Wyvern is important because it can help you to pop cards in the field (o.e your babycerasaurus or even opponent cards) and can help you extend and bring out more scrap monsters and build Apollousa with a respectable ammount of negates.Using Dark Ruler No More in the side deck, you can turn it into a Go-2nd Dino Deck and confuse the opponent. You can ditch the Super Poly / Predaplant / Starving Venom and Mystic Mine package in the side deck and use other cards of your personal choice. Gravedigger's Trap Hole is a good cheap alternative to deal with hand traps. If you are not on a budget of course you can use Nibiru and Ash as substitutes for the Effect Veilers (I recommend to not change the Psy-Frame Hand-trap line-up). Chain blocking with Lost World and Oviraptor is a nice start to combos and to prevent your dinos from getting their effects negated (either from Imperm or Handtraps). With Keystone and the Scrap Engine you can end up in a good board with many negates. Apollousa, Dolkka/Laggia, Naturia Beast and UCT is one nice example end board. Gallant Granite is helpful and can search you Keystone during your combos and manage to recycle Misc in a good flow. Dugares is helpful for OTKs (same goes for Pentestag). Furthermore, backrow removal is a must for the current meta (Twins, Tornado Dragon, Harpie's, Pankratops for either monsters or trap/spell cards etc.) so don't be hesitant to use the given options. Hope you liked my upload and of course any suggestions in order to make the deck better are welcome! Don't let the Dinos die in the current formats. :D

deck_excerpt: Standard Krawler build using the Magicians' Souls engine for consistency!
deck_description:
I've been working on a series of Krawler decks, trying to test out as many different builds as I can to see what creative deck-building solutions I can come up with. This list sorta fits into that category, but I'm not going to be doing as in-depth a review as I normally would, as its mostly a proof-of-concept build to test out the inclusion of Magicians' Souls in the build.

 

This is a fairly standard Krawler build; we have the 3 Soma, 3 Girsu, Lib in the extra, and a variety of link plays. Where this list diverges is the inclusion of Magicians' Souls, a tech card used in many other builds like the BASED pile and Prank-Kids decks. This card can special summon itself by sending Illusion of Chaos from deck to GY, and Illusion of Chaos can be placed from hand to the top of the deck to search Magicians' Souls. Once Souls is on the field, we can use its effect to send up to 2 Spell/Trap cards from hand or field to GY. In this build, we use this effect to get rid of dead-draws or once-per-turn spells that we have already used, as well as to get Mind Meld from hand to GY.

 

How does this card help the consistency of a Krawlers build? Well, our main play on turn 1 is to normal summon Girsu, sending Mind Meld, then use Girsu to make a token. We flip Girsu down with Soma's effect, summoning Soma, then use Soma to summon 2 more Krawlers from deck, face-up. We link off Soma and the token for Lib, setting Pawns to the field with Lib's effect. Then we link off the 2 Krawlers for Shaddoll Construct and fuse Construct with the face-down Girsu for Winda. Finally, we activate Mind Meld in GY, banishing it to summon Deus X to a zone a link monster points to. This is a very solid open, but we can't always guarantee that we will draw both Soma and Girsu, even if we include Small World. With Magicians' Souls included, we have a greater chance of drawing into a dark that we can use with Soma to make Winda, and we can sometimes fix a bad hand by sending Spell/Traps to draw. If we open Soma and Souls, with any normal-summonable monster, we can special summon Souls and discard any excess or unusable cards to draw. Then, we flip down Souls to summon Soma, and use Soma to get 2 face-up Krawlers to the field. We summon our other monster in hand, then link them off with Soma for Lib, using her effect to search Pawns/Mind Meld. Link the 2 Krawlers for Construct, and fusion summon Winda with Construct and Souls.

 

To take best advantage of Souls, we are running Cosmic Cyclone, which can be used from the GY to pop a face-up Spell/Trap (likely a floodgate/field spell). There are definitely arguments to be made about what fits and what does not in this list; Prosperity, a Spright/Frog package, and then there's the budget consideration. Speaking of budget, I'll start with that: I know this build is obscenely expensive for a Krawler list. If you wanted to run this list, but found the price prohibitive, you could always trim the Magicians' Souls and Illusion of Chaos to 1 a-piece. Also, there are many budget alternatives to extra deck staples, potentially using Pitknight Earlie as a substitute for Apollousa and Borrelsword instead of Zeus/Avramax. Pot of Prosperity is not just the most expensive card in the list, but it also lacks synergy with Magicians' Souls. If we use Prosperity, we can't draw off of Souls, and vice versa. We could try Extravagence, but I think Pot of Desires is the budget/alternative pick for this list. It does run the chance of hitting vital cards to our combo, but it is a +1 in card advantage, and it can always be used partially through our combo, once we have searched the necessary cards, to provide resources for next turn or extend our play. Another option, which will only add to the large price on this deck, is running a small Spright/Frog package. The advantage of this package is that if you don't find Souls or Girsu, you can still make Toadally Awesome and Spright Elf. This could be done with 1 Blue, 1 Jet, 1 Carrot/Red, 2 Starter, 2 Swap Frog, and 1 Ronintoadin. I don't think this is a good fit for the list, since we would be forced to choose between making Winda and making Toad, but it is an option.

 

Just to clarify a choice; Iblee is in the deck as a possible Small World bridge, but also to summon off of Gigantic Spright and then link into Spright Elf/I:P Masquerena if we draw Soma and don't find Girsu or Souls. Maybe this should be taken out of the list, but I like their inclusion for now.

 

Small World bridges:

Starter  ->  Bridge  ->  Goal

Any Krawler (but Axon) / Souls / World Armor / Girsu  ->  Magical Hound  ->  Any Krawler (but Axon) / Souls / World Armor / Girsu

Any Level 2 Krawler / Illusion of Chaos / World Armor  ->  Iblee  ->  Any Level 2 Krawler / Illusion of Chaos / World Armor

Girsu / Iblee / Soma  ->  Illusion of Chaos  ->  Girsu / Iblee / Soma

Magical Hound / Souls / Girsu / Soma  ->  World Armor  ->  Magical Hound / Souls / Girsu / Soma

 

I got a bit carried away on this one; I just meant to write a short summary! But I am glad I was able to spend some time on alternatives for the list, something that I wish more decklists included! Right now its very tricky to play yugioh on a moderate budget with several staples exceeding the $50 mark, and some propelling past $100 (US dollar). As always, please let me know what you thought! Do you agree with the list, disagree with the choices I made, or do you have an idea for a totally wild build that could use this core? Thanks for reading, and have a great day!

deck_excerpt: Turns out Nephthys were good all this time.
deck_description:
At this point you may be aware of the sheer strength of Spright, so I won't go into that part of the deck that much. Gigantic and Elf are insane, that's all you need to remember. So, what does Nephthys offer to the deck that Frogs or even Evil Twins doesn't? Absurd value.

Their gimmick being that to activate their effects they have to pop a card in your hand and start amassing advantage form that since all have effects when destroyed by card effects. Thus it meant that you'll go way down in card advantage to even begin to play like any other deck, and being a ritual deck just made it worse. This all changed with a relatively new piece of support and a series of design choices Konami has made that lead to this slow gimmick to turn into a hodgepoge of value.

It all starts with Conductor of Nephthys, one of the most insane pieces of support ever printed. It special summons a Nephthys ritual monster from the deck and treats it like a ritual summon, thus allowing it to trigger it's effects. The one you'll always going to summon is Devotee, which when ritual summoned summons another non-ritual Nepthys from the deck. This being Disciple, which by destroying a card in your hand searchs Matriarch which can revive a Nephthys monster from the GY. This guarantees four monsters on the field with a single ritual summon, but also makes Conductor the biggest hand trap target in the planet. But what if you'r opponent used all of them before you get Conductor on the field?

All Nephthys monsters worth a dime are level two, giving you access to Gigantic Spright and Spright Elf. You know which other monsters are level two as well? Diviner of the Heralds and Cyber Egg Angel. These two fixes one of the biggest weaknesses of the deck: getting to their ritual spell. And thanks to the Elf and Gigantic you don't have to commit to a normal summon for it. Diviner bieng the absolute best, by giving you the flexibility of a search or a pop by sending Arc Lights or N'tss. Meanwhile, Egg searches Ritual Sanctuary which not only hard ritual summons, but trades extra copies of Spright Starter or Rebirth of Nephthys (which through the course of your combo are most likely to have) for an extender and recycles them. The last Nephthys monster I also want to point out is Chaos Nephthys. By using Elf to revive Diviner during your opponent's turn and sending N'tss to pop a card they control, you can revive Chaos by banishing a light and a dark to also banish a card on the field and two from their GY, while also giving you an extra body for Masquerena into Apollousa.

The combo lines vary depening of the amount of Sprights you have, but as long as you can resolve Gigantic or Conductor you can go full combo.

By having Conductor or a way to get to it (like Preparation) and Spright Starter your combo may look something like this (also keep in mind your zone placement):

Spright Starter > Summon Blue > Search Jet and summon it > Search another Starter > XYZ summon Gigantic Spright > Summon Diviner (and prevent Nibiru) > Send Herald of Arc Lights and search Rebirth of Nephthys > Ritual summon Conductor by tributing Diviner > CH1 Conductor, CH2 Diviner > Summon Egg and Devotee > CH1 Devotee, CH2 Egg > Search Ritual Sanctuary and summon Disciple > Disciple effect to search Matriarch > Use Disciple and Devotee to link summon the nephthys link > Search Chaos nephthys with it and recycle your ritual spell > Use the effect of Devotee to revie itself by destroying Chaos Nephthys in your hand > Link Devotee and the Nephthys link into Elf > Elf revives Diviner and link it and Eff into Halqifibrax to summon The Agent of Mystery - Earth > Link Earth and Gigantic into Pitknight Earlie > Finally, normal summon Matriarch and use her effect to revive any Nepthys level two in your GY and link summon Masquerena.

Now during your opponent's turn you can use Elf to revive Diviner to send N'tss and pop a card, thus triggering Chaos Nephthys in your GY to revive itself and banishing three cards (keep in mind that for it to trigger there also needs to be a card on the other field for it to banish). You can use Halqifibrax effect to go into Formula Synchron, draw one card and synchro it and the remaining level two on your field for a Herald of Arc Lights (you could also make Baronee, but the extra deck is extremely small and decided to keep the utility of Arc Light over Baronee). At this point, depending on where you placed Pitknight you could've also negated a monster's effect as well. Finally you use Masquarena to go into Apollouse with the remaining materials on the field and swing for game with Accesscode on the crackback.

The biggest downsides of this version of the deck is that you trade space for handtraps in favor of combo pieces. The deck lives and dies by their ritual spell. If you get prevented of getting to it, you're absolutely dead. The extra deck is extremely tight and since you play with a bunch of one-offs Prosperity is the better option over Desires, but there are games where I used it and found myself in really need of the cards I banished on the following turn (this version straight up vomits your whole extra deck). Possibly the most annoying yet funny downside is that all the monsters are really, really small. If your opponent manages to survive until the batttle phase and has a monster with more than 1600 atk you're kinda screwed. If konami prints a XYZ monster with a lingering effect that pumps your other monsters even by just 500 atk it would seriously consider playing it over Accesscode.

deck_excerpt: I actually play Red-Eyes cards I swear
deck_description: Anyone who was ever tried to build a Red-Eyes deck in the last couple of years knows this feeling: you add Dragon Link cards to the deck to make it better and before you know you are just playing regular Dragon Link cause the Red-Eyes cards are not good. With this deck, I believe I have overcomed this predicament, what this list does is make the basic Dragon Link end board of Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres + Borreload Dragon but instead of going for Seal of the Heavenly Spheres you link summon Predaplant Verte Anaconda, use it's effect and summon Red-Eyes Slash Dragon, sending a copy of The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots to the graveyard which you can then banish to search for a monster negate in Phantom Knights' Fog Blade; additionaly, Slash Dragon can send the link monster that Borreload equips to itself to the graveyard to negate and destroy an opponent's card that targets one of your cards, that's the main synergy between the Rokket and Red-Eyes archetypes outside of the fact that they are both mainly dark dragon monsters. If you are familiar with the Dragon Link strategy, then you should have no problems playing this deck, if you are not familiar then you can just search one of the many combo guides and tutorials out there, since Dragon Link is very popular. Depending on your starting hand you can add more interruptions to your board: if you have many extenders (Mainly the Chaos Dragons Wyverburster and Collapserpent) you can go for both Heavenly Spheres and Verte in addition to Borreload, and if you have access to Black Metal Dragon you can get Red-Eyes Fang with Chain to equip an opponent's monster to your Slash Dragon (You can also get Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon instead, which can summon back Black Metal Dragon and once said card goes to the graveyard again for, for example, a link summon, then search the Fang with Chain, since Black Metal Dragon's search effect is not once per turn).

deck_excerpt: Turbo out Krawlers with Soma, then synch them off with P.U.N.K.s!
deck_description:
Hi there! This is another deck in a series where I try to build as many different P.U.N.K. builds as I can, pushing my creativity and deck-building skills in the process! This build blends Krawlers new ability to summon out lots of bodies with Soma, with P.U.N.K. synchro-summon toolbox! This list is far from final, and can most definitely be improved, but I hope it serves as inspiration for someone to come along and one-up this build! To start, I'll go over what the disparate parts of this deck do and how they work together, my reasoning for the ratios, combo lines, and thoughts on what can be added/improved.

 

So Krawlers, and honorary Krawlers (looking at you, Girsu), have a lot of potential in deckbuilding, but rely on solid support. The Krawler Extra Deck mons, which I love dearly, do not make for a very strong endboard. Really, the area where Krawlers seem to struggle the most is in taking advantage of their resources on-board. You can easily get three mons onto the board with Soma's effect, and can guarantee a Deus X summon and a link-2 off of Girsu, but they usually rely on Shaddoll Construct, the Ghostrick UDF package, or generic link climbing to make and break boards. P.U.N.K.s have one of the most open extra decks in the game, as long as we're talking about Synchros! Powerful bosses like Psychic End Punisher, and resource fountains like Chaos Ruler, are as easy for P.U.N.K. to make as summoning tuners is for Halq, who they can also access very readily. When we combine these strengths, we can pretty reliably end on strong end boards; one example being Baronne/Chengying, Naturia Beast, Winda, Halq, a set Deus X, a set Pawns, and a set Dangerous Gabu.

 

To fit everything in, and still give this deck a good grind-game, I had to play with the ratios for this deck. We want to see Soma and Girsu as often as possible, so we run them at 3. The P.U.N.K. engine is one place where we save space, playing one-a-piece, except for Deer Note and Foxy Tune who we have at 2. We are on Garbage Lord as a level 5 extender, 2 Garbage Lords and 2 Garbage Ogres. The hand traps, whose place in the deck is debatable, are Ghost Ogre and Ghost Belle at 2 a piece. These can be Small World bridges, but we also don't want to see multiples in our opening hands, so we just run them at 2. Dark Ruler, however, is much more powerful in the current meta, and I feel it warrants its ratio of 3. 2 Pot of Avarice may seem suspect, but we use it to recover our resources to make follow-up plays on our future turns. The Extra Deck will be shown more fully in the combo section, but one piece of tech that I'm not sold on yet is Desert Locusts. We summon them with Halq on the opponent's turn, discarding a card from their hand and letting us Synchro summon a mon. I feel like it under-performs, but I want to do more testing before replacing it.

 

Combos! In a P.U.N.K. build you know there are going to be lots of combos, and lots of steps in each combo, so lets get to it!

 

Starter(s): combo->

Soma and a non-starter mon (non-Ze Amin low level P.U.N.K., Krawler, Garbage Lord, etc): Summon the non-starter monster, and flip them down to special summon Soma. Use Soma to summon 2 Krawlers from deck, both face-down. End the turn, and hope for the best! This one is kind of a joke; we should rarely find ourselves in a scenario where we have no extenders or starters in our hand. In a more pure Krawler build, this hand is much more powerful, as we can make an Extra Deck Krawler that floats on removal, or Subterror Behemoth Fiendess, who summons another flip-mon from hand. This build sacrifices those possibilities for a greater potential payoff at the end of the combo.

Soma and Girsu (and nothing else): Summon Girsu, sending Mind Meld from deck to GY on summon. Use Girsu to make a token, then flip down Girsu to summon Soma and use Soma to summon 2 Krawlers face-up. Link Soma and the token off for Lib, and use Lib to set Pawns to the field. Link the 2 Krawlers off for Shaddoll Construct and use her effect to fusion summon Winda, using herself and the face-down Girsu as material. Activate Mind Meld in the GY, banishing itself to set Deus X-Krawler to the field. We end on Lib, Winda, set Deus X, and a set Pawns.

Just a P.U.N.K. starter: So, to explain, a P.U.N.K. starter is Ze Amin, Foxy Tune, Ogre Dance, or Emergency Teleport, but there are other starters that require more cards in hand. For this combo, we assume that only one of these three have been drawn. If you have Ogre Dance, use it to search Ze Amin, and if you have E-Tele summon Ze Amin. I'll explain the Foxy Tune line after this, as it is a bit different. Activate Ze Amin to search Foxy Tune, then use Foxy Tune to summon a P.U.N.K. The simplest P.U.N.K. to summon is Deer Note, as then you can make Chaos Ruler, bring back Ze Amin, and make Psychic End Punisher, but I prefer to use the Sharakusai line. In that case, summon Sharakusai with Foxy Tune. If you started with only Foxy Tune in hand, use them to special summon Ze Amin, then use Ze Amin to add Ogre Dance, who then can add Sharakusai, who you can then normal summon. There! Both of the combo lines have converged. You should have a Ze Amin and a Sharakusai on field. Use Sharakusai to summon Rising Carp with Ze Amin, and use Carp's effect to summon 2 mons from deck. Summon Wa Gon/Madame Spider and Deer Note, then Synch these two off for Jam Dragon or Chaos Ruler. Chaos Ruler can draw you some cards, and you can get another piece of interruption on field or in hand, so in this case I prefer it, but Jam Dragon can do much the same. Either way, summon the mon, activate the effects on summon, and the Deer Note in GY, summoning back Sharakusai. If you summoned Jam Dragon, I would advise the mon you get off of Carp to be Wa Gon, so that you can find the field spell before activating Jam Dragon and draw 2 more cards (1 from Jam, 1 from Madame Spider, searched off of Jam), in addition to the Trap searched off of Madame Spider. Here you can make Psychic End Punisher, or if you make Chaos Ruler, Halq, who then summons Ghost Ogre (she can use her effect on field during the opponent's turn). Reborn Chaos Ruler using its effect, then you can either make Psychic End on your turn, or Amazing Dragon on the Opponent's. Whew! That was a lot of text, sorry for that. EDIT: Also, any lv8 and Halq on board can mean Baronne/Chengying if you tag out the Halq for Formula Synchron.

The other P.U.N.K. starters: So, if you have Sharakusai and another P.U.N.K. in hand, or a P.U.N.K. with our extender in hand (Garbage Lord), we can still pop off! If you have Sharakusai, summon them, then use their effect to make Carp. Use Carp to get Ze Amin and Deer Note, and search Foxy Tune with Ze Amin. Here you can make either Jam Dragon, Chaos Ruler, or both! If you want to make one or the other, follow the steps in the guide above (though you may not have the field spell for Jam Dragon), but if you want to make both use the Foxy Tune in hand to summon another Deer Note from deck. Now, use the Ze Amin and a Deer Note to make Chaos Ruler, summoning Sharakusai off of the Deer Note's effect. Make Halq with Sharakusai and Chaos Ruler, summoning a level 3 Tuner (any of our Tuners), and summon back Chaos Ruler if it behooves you. Use that tuner and the second Deer Note to make Jam Dragon, searching a lv 3 P.U.N.K., or use that tuner and Chaos Ruler to make an Amazing Dragon / Psychic End. If you have the Jam Dragon or Chaos Ruler and Halq, you can tag out the Halq to get a Formula Synchron and make Chengying or Baronne. If you have Garbage Lord and a P.U.N.K. in hand, summon both, make Chaos Ruler, and hopefully

 

Now we get into the meaty combos!

Girsu and E-Tele: Girsu eats our normal summon, so we need a special summon to extend our combo with him. Perform the Girsu combo, summoning, sending Mind Meld to GY, make and link with your token for Lib, use lib to set Pawns, and use Mind Meld to set Deus X. Okay, now you can use Emergency Teleport to summon Ze Amin. Ze Amin searches Foxy Tune, which can either summon Deer Note, or summon Sharakusai who later searches Deer Note through Carp. Once you have a lv 3 P.U.N.K. and Deer Note, you can do one of the final P.U.N.K. plays from the previous section; Ending with Chaos Ruler, Halq, a set Deus, and a set Dangerous Gabu.

Soma and a P.U.N.K. starter: The goal here is to get to Chaos Ruler and Halq, so perform the P.U.N.K. combo with that in mind, making Chaos Ruler, summoning back Sharakusai off of Deer Note's effect, then link them off for Halq, summoning a lv3 Tuner. Summon back Chaos Ruler with their effect, then flip them down with Soma to summon Soma. Use Soma to summon 2 Krawlers face-up, then synch Soma and the lv3 Tuner for Naturia Beast. Link the 2 Krawlers for Shaddoll Construct, then use Construct and the face-down Chaos Ruler to make Winda.

Soma, Girsu, and E-Tele: Summon Girsu, sending Mind Meld, then create the token, use Soma to summon itself by flipping down Girsu. Use E-Tele to summon Ze Amin, searching Foxy Tune with Ze, summon Sharakusai off of Foxy, fuse Sharakusai and Ze Amin for Carp, then use Carp to fetch Wa Gon and Deer Note. Get the field spell with Wa Gon, then Synch for Chaos Ruler, summoning back Sharakusai with Deer Note. Link Sharakusai and Deer note for Halq, summoning a lv 3 Tuner, then summon 2 Krawlers with Soma. Use Soma and the Tuner to make Naturia Beast, then link the 2 Krawlers for Construct. Bring back Chaos Ruler using their effect, and then make Winda with Construct and Girsu. An end board with Nat Beast, Winda, Halq, and Chaos Ruler. You can summon Formula Synchron on the opponent's turn, but you cannot make Baronne/Chengying unless the opponent destroys Winda first. 

 

Small World Bridges:

Starter  ->  Bridge  ->  End

Any Earth / Any Machine  ->  Magical Hound  ->  Any Earth / Any Machine

Ghost Ogre/Belle / Girsu / Orochi / Ogre Dance / Necro  ->  Garbage Lord  ->  Ghost Ogre/Belle / Girsu / Orochi / Ogre Dance / Necro

 

 

Okay! Finishing thoughts; I think the combination of these engines really opens up a lot of Synchro potential for the Krawlers, and gives P.U.N.K.s a very interesting extender in Soma. This combination makes very menacing end-boards and can tool-box you out of many scenarios. However, there is an extreme weakness to Dark Ruler / Forbidden Droplet in this list, so maybe we should be siding Blizzard or Judgement. Anyways, what did you think? Hopefully this deck description has been informative and helpful, or at least entertaining! If you have any thoughts on what could be done differntly for this deck, or other ways to use this combination, please let me know! I really appreciate you, and hope you have a good day!

deck_description: In the side deck, I put other plant archetypes/plant support I played around with in this deck. Some might make the deck better, but I just find it more fun with a pure variant.
marincess deck

This deck will leave you on a pretty insane endboard and without crossout designator and other hand traps, you can play through negate boards going second, or create an unbeatable board going first. 

Note-This is link spam deck and you need a couple of things to go right.

1. Get a Telfon in the graveyard and one telfon on the field

2. If you have two telfons in hand plus a one for one or a gadget gamer you can normal gadget gamer;use second effect bring out telfon and hauler, then use hauler to get other telfon in grave then go to combo

If you want more crossout targets you could replace the field spells and pot of prosperity with the Dpe set

Now to the combo! (It requires the two attack position telfons on field)

Firstly get telfon on field and in the most ideal use machine duplication to get three on field if only you need two

use the telfon that used it's effect already to link off *for every link use that telfon so the other telfon can bring the telfon back*

Telfon into relinquished Anema BTB (bring other telfon back)

Telfon and anema into halq and using halq bring an earth machine and put it in a zone halq doesn't point to

BTB then use telfon and halq target to go into acient gear link. Use effect to get gear box. Use gear box to get tunneler. BTB then use spec tunnuler using telfon

BTB then use tunnler telfon and ancient gear to go into G golem link 4 in corner link spot

BTB then go into anema using telfon. then using telfon, anema, and halq go into apollusa

BTB into linkuriboh BTB then using telfon and kuriboh go into binary sorceres in middle spot so there's a space between g golem, apolluse, and binary

BTB then bring link kuriboh back from grave using telfon then make dagda after BTB

BTB again dagda chain link 2 to set scythe then BTB again so you can go into trigate wizard

Using the tunneler in grave you should be able to use it's gy effect to shuffle and draw 2

Lastly go into I:P using the last two telfons and you can quick effect during oppenents turn to bring out griffon or avermax

 

If setup fails draw into rebuilder or eschatos to shuffle and go into combo all over again

Side deck is interchangables and more crossout targets and you can even slide dpe in their and anti spell fragrance so griffon can set it for your opponents turn

deck_excerpt: This is the deck DistantCoder is using for his Diamond 1 climb on season 9 of Master Duel's ranked ladder.
deck_description: Midrange deck aiming to control the game with handtraps and a very recursive engine. A very strong deck that is great for beginners who want to take their skill to the next level as Salamangreat doesn't punish inexperienced players but does reward skilled players with its high power ceiling!

It's been awhile but I've been keeping with the game. In fact with the recent release of TAMA into the TCG, gave new purpose in my renovation. Below is the deck list and how each piece works.

Main Deck

Monsters

1x Psy-Frame epsilon

2x Psy-Frame Alpha, Beta, Gamma, and Delta, along with Necroface, Psychic wheeleder and Tracker

3x Tour guide and Sangan

 

Spell and Traps

1x Runick Allure, Gold Sarc

2x Runick Fountain, Psy-Frame Circuit, Runick Flashing Fire, Smiting, and Tip, along with Emergency Teleport, Piercing the Darkness and Psy-Frame Overload

3x Pot of Acquisitiveness

 

Extra Deck

1x Psychic End Punisher, Swordsoul Chengying, Psy-Frame Zeta and Omega, Chaos Magical Dragon, Virtual world Shenshen and Jiujiu, Dragon Dive, and Underworld Goddess

2x Runick Munin and Geri, and Psy-Frame Lambda

 

Side Deck

3x Ghost Ogre

2x Runick Freezing Curses and Destruction, Psychic Feel Zone

1x Runick Allure, Emergency Teleport, Crystron Halq, Formula Synchron, Stardust Charge Warrior, Geomathmech Final Sigma

 

TelekiNOsis was always my favorite deck I've created and what better way to give it an upgrade than to give it access to new ways to make your opponent sweat?

The main deck plays pretty much the same. Counter your opponents moves with your own, strategically snipe enemy cards from the field while now being able to Thanos snap their deck away with each quick play spell. Ideally it pops off more when you play second but it also has plays if you are forced to play first. When siding, it put aside time consuming plays in favor for OTK potential in which has two. The first is decking an opponent out (which is your more trusted possibility), while the second is punching for game in one shot.

Each card meshes well with one another and I'm calling it now, this just may be one of the best ways to use Runicks. Til next time.
